ğŸ” ğŸ“ Problem Understanding  
â¡ï¸ ğŸ¯ **Input:** Integer `colNum` representing an Excel column number  
â¡ï¸ ğŸ¯ **Output:** Corresponding column title as a string  

ğŸ“ ğŸ”¢ Constraints  
â¡ï¸ `colNum > 0`  

ğŸ”„ ğŸ› ï¸ Edge Cases  
â¡ï¸ Smallest column number (1 â†’ "A")  
â¡ï¸ Large column number (e.g., `702 â†’ "ZZ"`)  

ğŸ’¡ ğŸ” Approach  
ğŸ”¹ **Using Division and Modulus**  
  ğŸ”¹ Columns follow a **base-26** system  
  ğŸ”¹ Subtract `1` from `colNum` to make it **0-based**  
  ğŸ”¹ Find the remainder when dividing by `26`, convert to a character (`A-Z`)  
  ğŸ”¹ Append to result and divide `colNum` by `26` for next iteration  
  ğŸ”¹ Reverse the result to get the correct column title  

â³ â±ï¸ Time Complexity: **O(log colNum)**  
ğŸ’¾ ğŸ—ï¸ Space Complexity: **O(1)**  

ğŸ“ ğŸ”¢ Pseudo Code  
```plaintext
initialize empty string builder
while colNum > 0:
    decrement colNum by 1 (convert to 0-based)
    find remainder when divided by 26
    convert remainder to corresponding character ('A' + remainder)
    append character to string
    update colNum by dividing by 26
reverse the string and return
```

ğŸ’» ğŸ”¡ Code Implementation  
```java
public String convertToTitle(int colNum) {
    StringBuilder str = new StringBuilder();
    while (colNum > 0) {
        colNum--;  
        int rem = colNum % 26;
        char ch = (char) ('A' + rem);
        str.append(ch);
        colNum /= 26;
    }
    return str.reverse().toString();
}
```

